climbs.name: Sweet and Sour
climbs.fa: Jared Hancock, Skip Wolfe, Mark Ryan 2005

content.description: Climb the obvious short dihedral to the right of Yu Stin Ki Pu.
content.protection: Small to small-ish gear. Might take something as large as a #1 Camalot. There used to be bolt anchors on top. Who knows now?
content.location: Between Yu Stin Ki Pu and Ai Bang Mai.

content.description: Stick clipping the first bolt is highly recommended. The crux is getting to and past the first bolt and falling here would be ugly. The climber needs to be careful not to kick their belayer while starting the route. It's very balancy. The anchors are a bit hidden from below but obvious once you pull the ledge.
content.location: On the upper level about Beta Spewers. From the top of the trail, walk left to access the upper level and then traverse right being careful to not rocks on those below. A set of belay anchors below a blunt arete mark the start of the route.

content.description:
When you walk into The Practice Wall, this route is the squeeze chimney just right of the trad route Short and Sweet (5.7). The route identifier for this route lists it at 5.6 but there is no way it is that difficult. The RRG guidebook has it listed as 5.2 so I used that rating.

Step into the chimney and use huge feet and hands and climb up to the light above. Inside the chimney you have an abundance of holds for your feet and hands. The crux is the top out.
content.protection: The route was originally free-soloed, when I climbed it I didn;t see any spots for gear.
content.location: Just right of Short and Sweet (5.7)

content.description:
Climb the left of the three slab routes that you see first when you walk up the trail to the Practice Wall.

An easy start leads to and fun reachy crux about halfway through the climb. This is a really cool route which has a nice flowing crux.
content.protection: Two bolts and rappel rings.  Stick clip recommended.
content.location: On the first slab/ low angle face you see when you reach the Practice Wall, this the the left most of the three bolted routes.

content.description: Start up the chimney formed by the large flake and top it out. Then move up and right (or right and up) to the first high bolt. A long stick clip is required to snag it from the ground. Some weird moves get you to a nice rest. Pump out to the anchors.
content.location: Shares a start with Beastly Traverse by heading up a chimney formed by a huge flake. Follows bolts to the right of flake.

content.description: This dinky dihedral is harder than it looks.  The corner crack starts off fingertips-thin, and there's not much in the way of feet on the faces.  In spite of its short length, not a good choice for neophyte trad leaders.
content.protection: Light rack.  Small cams and nuts, then a #3 Camalot or equivalent to protect the topout moves.
content.location: Starts in an obvious dihedral at the top of the approach trail, just right of three short sport lines.  Shares bolted anchors with Low Exposure (use a directional).

content.description:
The crux comes in reaching the chains. The is a really cool clipping open hand pinch to clip the chains.

This is the best of the three routes on this section of wall in my opinion.
content.location: Located between Slabalito and Low Exposure.

content.description: Climb the left leaning ramp up to what looks like a plated face. Crimp and heel hook your way off the ramp and onto the face. Pretty much continuous crimping after leaving the ramp. Really neat route.
content.location: This route is on the right side of the wall and is the first bolted route as you start up the hill. Left leaning ramp to plated face are obvious features.

climbs.name: Mercenary of the Mandarin Chicken
climbs.fa: Karla Carandang, Jared Hancock, Skip Wolfe, 2005

content.description:
This is the arete to the left of Beta Spewer, the route is different from everything to the left because it is overhung with big hold, a good introduction to RRG.

The crux comes between the second bolt and the anchors, just look for good holds the are there.
content.location: Arete just left of Beta Spewer.

climbs.name: Low Exposure
climbs.fa: Jared Hancock, Sierra Jones, Mark Ryan - 2005

content.description: Easier start gains a thin crimpy section near the top. This route tops out and the anchors are located above the lip on a large boulder. If you follow the bolt lines directly it is harder than 5.8, the 5.8 climbs just right of the bolt line then shifts back left at the top.
content.location: This is one the short vertical wall that is the first thing you see at the Practice Wall, this is the right most sport route on that wal just left of Short and Sweet 5.7

content.description:
Most people solo this one but it does take good fist-sized gear.

A low crux leads to easier climbing at the top.

This is a good route to demonstrate how to properly place gear.
content.location: next route right of Slither and Squeeze 5.2 about 40 feet left of that route around the corner.

content.description:
This route was an open project until recently when it was done at 12b.

I have found that most hard climbers avoid the practice wall like the plague due to the short walls and easy routes but I would urge all of you to swing by for at least this route!

The Handout starts on a large right undercling when you reach out left to a worse undercling and throw a large cross to a good ledge. This incredibly fun move sets the tone for the rest of the route with a solid pump factor with some low percentage stabs to pockets, and a couple of bad pinches.

Great flow and awesome holds (in this climbers opinion) definitely make this route a must do at the grade!
content.location: far left side of the roof section of practice wall. easily seen by its large undercling pocket start

content.description: This is an easy to protect trad route.  It is a fun way to continue practicing trad on Practice wall.  Kate's 1st trad is even easier.
content.protection: The route takes medium size cams, smaller nuts, and if you want you can even place one of your bigger cams.  There are two ways to exit off this route.  The first is to use the bolted anchors of Dragon's Mouth 5.6.  The second it to rappel off a small tree.
content.location: This route is just to the right of Dragon's mouth.  Dragon's Mouth begins in the chimney about ten feet to the left of Crescent Moon.

content.description: Chimney next to Dragon's Tail.  The route is a little dirty, and lowering back through the chimney is awkward and is probably just like lowering into the mouth of a dragon with all the protruding "teeth" on the sides of the walls.
content.protection: Well-bolted route like most in Muir Valley.
content.location: Right of Dragon's Tail.  Left of Crescent Moon.

climbs.name: Crescent Moon
climbs.fa: Mark Ryan, JJ, Skip Wolfe, Jared Hancock

content.description: bouldery start gains good moves to a solid reachy move past a blank section. depending on how you decide to move after the second bolt, the difficulty can vary!
content.location: far side of practice wall, past the overhanging ceiling area.

climbs.name: Crescendo
climbs.fa: Jared Hancock, J.J., Skip Wolfe, Mark Ryan, Amy Moore 2005

content.description: The start is the toughest section.
content.location: This route is to the right of Crescent Moon.  After walking up to practice wall take a right.  Head along the trail until you start finding sport routes.  The route is labeled with a little metal name plate.

content.description: Kind of an awkward route and a bit tough to onsite. The pocket sequence can be a bit confusing, especially towards the top.
content.location: Far left route at Practice Wall.

content.description: Short Crack with tough boulder problem down low. Low traffic, lots of spiders.
content.protection: Hand size gear and a few bolts
content.location: Overhanging crack to the right of "Beta Spewer".

climbs.name: Beta Spewer
climbs.fa: Jared Hancock, Karla Carandang, Skip Wolfe, Mark Ryan - 2005

content.description: Climb okay holds up to a nice side pull/jug then get the next side pull.  Get established and reach for a good crimp.  Reach up high for a giant jug that looks like a horn. Go left a bit on good holds then fire up to a decent hold then reach the anchors with big jugs again.
content.protection:
2 Bolts to Rap Rings

Stick clip first bolt
content.location:
Once you're at the cliff go right and it's the last short climb on your left as you come around the corner

You will notice a lot of chalk on the holds

climbs.name: Another One Fights the Rust
climbs.fa: Jared Hancock, Skip Wolfe, Mark Ryan, J.J.

content.description: Stick clip the first bolt. Haul past a pretty hard move to easier but not very good climbing to a dirty ledge. Can Continue up a 5.7 slabby sport climb to the top.
content.protection: A few mid size cams and one bolt to bolted anchors.
content.location: From the short easy slabs at the top of the trail walk left and up a hill. This is a right facing dihedral you will come to.

climbs.name: Ai Bang Mai Fa Kin Ni
climbs.fa: Jared Hancock, Karla Carandang, Jenny Wagner, Mark Ryan, 2005

content.description:
This is a short face to the right of Sweet and Sour 5.5.

You can climb either side of the bolts. The start is the crux followed by more moderate climbing. For an added treat sit start it.
content.location: bolted line right of Sweet and Sour 5.5 trad route.

climbs.name: Acrophobiacs Anonymous
climbs.fa: Jared Hancock, Karla Carandang, Jane Maurer, Mark Ryan - 2005

content.description: Start with a low crux below the first bolt. Then work your way up the easy low angle face on big holds and big feet. This route is pretty sandy.
content.location: On the right/middle of the wall just left of the easy trad route Kate's 1st Trad Lead 5.1

content.description: After climbing Another One Fights the Rust the route climbs low angle juggy slab to the top of the cliff. It is dirty but solid rock.
content.location: Second pitch of Another One Fights the Rust.

climbs.name: [Redacted]
climbs.fa: Jared Hancock, Skip Wolfe, Mark Ryan - 2005

content.description: This short climbs has an easy bottom to a crux just before the chains. Climb past two bolts to the anchors using large edges until the crux which has thinner hands and feet.
content.location: Between Sweet and Sour 5.5 (Trad) and Acrophobiacs Anonymous 5.4 (Sport)
